# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: javafx
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:javafx/data-binding] In computer programming, **data-binding** is a general technique that binds data sources from the provider and consumer together and synchronizes them.
[src:javafx/data-binding] This is usually done with two data/information sources with different languages, as in XML data binding and UI data binding.
[src:javafx/data-binding] In UI data binding, data and information objects of the same language, but different logic function are bound together (e.g., Java UI elements to Java objects).
[src:javafx/data-binding] In a data binding process, each data change is reflected automatically by the elements that are bound to the data.
[src:javafx/data-binding] The term data binding is also used in cases where an outer representation of data in an element changes, and the underlying data is automatically updated to reflect this change.
[src:javafx/data-binding] As an example, a change in a `TextBox` element could modify the underlying data value.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:javafx/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:javafx/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Writing in the Java programming language is the main way to produce code that will be deployed as byte code in a Java virtual machine (JVM); byte code compilers are also available for other languages, including Ada, JavaScript, Kotlin (Google's preferred Android language), Python, and Ruby.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In addition, several languages have been designed to run natively on the JVM, including Clojure, Groovy, and Scala.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java syntax borrows heavily from C and C++, but object-oriented features are modeled after Smalltalk and Objective-C.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Memory management is handled through integrated automatic garbage collection performed by the JVM.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The latest version is Java 26 released in March 2026.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The latest long-term support (LTS) version, Java 25 released in September 2025, it is one of a few LTS versions still supported, down to Java 8 LTS.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Oracle extended support for Java 6 ended in December 2018.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] As an open source platform, Java has many distributors, including Amazon, IBM, Azul Systems, and AdoptOpenJDK.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Distributions include Amazon Corretto, Zulu, AdoptOpenJDK, and Liberica.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Regarding Oracle, it distributes Java 8, and also makes available e.g.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java 11, both also currently supported LTS versions.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Oracle (and others) "highly recommend that you uninstall older versions of Java" than Java 8, because of serious risks due to unresolved security issues.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Since Java 9 (as well as versions 10, 12–16, 18–20, and 22–24) are no longer supported, Oracle advises its users to "immediately transition" to a supported version.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Oracle released the last free-for-commercial-use public update for the legacy Java 8 LTS in January 2019, and will continue to support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Java platform is a suite of programs that facilitate developing and running programs written in the Java programming language.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] A Java platform includes an execution engine (called a virtual machine), a compiler and a set of libraries; there may also be additional servers and alternative libraries that depend on the requirements.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java platforms have been implemented for a wide variety of hardware and operating systems with a view to enable Java programs to run identically on all of them.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Java platform consists of several programs, each of which provides a portion of its overall capabilities.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] For example, the Java compiler, which converts Java source code into Java bytecode (an intermediate language for the JVM), is provided as part of the Java Development Kit (JDK).
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Java Runtime Environment (JRE), complementing the JVM with a just-in-time (JIT) compiler, converts intermediate bytecode into native machine code on the fly.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Java platform also includes an extensive set of libraries.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The essential components in the platform are the Java language compiler, the libraries, and the runtime environment in which Java intermediate bytecode executes according to the rules laid out in the virtual machine specification.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java Platform, Standard Edition (Java SE) is a computing platform, technical standard for execution of applications on independent *Java-supported* platforms as such portable code for desktop and server environments.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java SE was formerly known as Java 2 Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE).
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The platform uses the Java programming language and is part of the Java software-platform family.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java SE defines a range of general-purpose APIs—such as Java APIs for the Java Class Library—and also includes the Java Language Specification and the Java Virtual Machine Specification.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] OpenJDK is the official reference implementation since version 7.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Jakarta EE, formerly Java Platform, Enterprise Edition (Java EE) and Java 2 Platform, Enterprise Edition (J2EE), is a set of specifications, extending Java SE with specifications for enterprise features such as distributed computing and web services.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Jakarta EE applications are run on reference runtimes, which can be microservices or application servers, which handle transactions, security, scalability, concurrency and management of the components they are deploying.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The heart of the Java platform is the "virtual machine" that executes Java bytecode programs.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] This bytecode is the same no matter what hardware or operating system the program is running under.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] However, new versions, such as for Java 10 (and earlier), have made small changes, meaning the bytecode is in general only forward compatible.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] There is a *just in time* (JIT) compiler within the *Java virtual machine* (JVM).
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The JIT compiler translates the Java bytecode into native processor instructions at run-time and caches the native code in memory during execution.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The use of bytecode as an intermediate language permits Java programs to run on any platform that has a virtual machine available.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The use of a JIT compiler means that Java applications, after a short delay during loading and once they have "warmed up" by being all or mostly JIT-compiled, tend to run about as fast as native programs.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Since JRE version 1.2, Sun's JVM implementation has included a just-in-time compiler instead of an interpreter.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Although Java programs are cross-platform or platform independent, the code of the Java virtual machines (JVM) that execute these programs is not.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Every supported operating platform has its own JVM.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Java Development Kit (JDK) is a software development kit for development of a Java platform application.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The JDK is designed to be mainly used to communicate with the Java Runtime Environment (JRE), but it *can* be replaced by other JDK-based languages which can communicate with the JRE and JVM.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Furthermore, Java bytecode *can* be compiled statically directly into native code only with a JVM but without the necessity of the Java runtime environment running dynamically.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] It implements the Java Language Specification (JLS) and the Java Virtual Machine Specification (JVMS) and provides the Standard Edition (SE) of the Java Application Programming Interface (API).
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] It is derivative of the community driven OpenJDK which Oracle stewards.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] It provides software for working with Java applications.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Examples of included software are the Java virtual machine, a compiler, performance monitoring tools, a debugger, and other utilities that Oracle considers useful for Java programmers.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Oracle releases the current version of the software under the Oracle No-Fee Terms and Conditions (NFTC) license.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Oracle releases binaries for the x86-64 architecture for Windows, macOS, and Linux based operating systems, and for the aarch64 architecture for macOS and Linux.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Previous versions supported the Oracle Solaris operating system and SPARC architecture.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Oracle's primary implementation of the JVMS is known as HotSpot.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The *Java Runtime Environment (JRE)* released by Oracle is a freely available software distribution containing a stand-alone JVM (HotSpot), the Java standard library (Java Class Library), a configuration tool, and—until its discontinuation in JDK 9—a browser plug-in.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] It is the most common Java environment installed on personal computers in the laptop and desktop form factor.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Mobile phones including feature phones and early smartphones that ship with a JVM are most likely to include a JVM meant to run applications targeting Micro Edition of the Java platform.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Meanwhile, most modern smartphones, tablet computers, and other handheld PCs that run Java apps are most likely to do so through support of the Android operating system, which includes an open source virtual machine incompatible with the JVM specification.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The last Oracle JRE implementation, regardless of its licensing scheme, was 9.0.4.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Since Java Platform SE 9, the whole platform also was grouped into modules.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The modularization of Java SE implementations allows developers to bundle their applications together with all the modules used by them, instead of solely relying on the presence of a suitable Java SE implementation in the user device.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In most modern operating systems (OSs), a large body of reusable code is provided to simplify the programmer's job.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] This code is typically provided as a set of dynamically loadable libraries that applications can call at runtime.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Because the Java platform is not dependent on any specific operating system, applications cannot rely on any of the pre-existing OS libraries.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Instead, the Java platform provides a comprehensive set of its own standard class libraries containing many of the same reusable functions commonly found in modern operating systems.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Most of the system library is also written in Java.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] For instance, the Swing library paints the user interface and handles the events itself, eliminating many subtle differences between how different platforms handle components.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Java class libraries serve three purposes within the Java platform.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] First, like other standard code libraries, the Java libraries provide the programmer a well-known set of functions to perform common tasks, such as maintaining lists of items or performing complex string parsing.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Second, the class libraries provide an abstract interface to tasks that would normally depend heavily on the hardware and operating system.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Tasks such as network access and file access are often heavily intertwined with the distinctive implementations of each platform.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The `java.net` and `java.io` libraries implement an abstraction layer in native OS code, then provide a standard interface for the Java applications to perform those tasks.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The word "Java", alone, usually refers to Java programming language that was designed for use with the Java platform.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Programming languages are typically outside of the scope of the phrase "platform", although the Java programming language was listed as a core part of the Java platform before Java 7.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The language and runtime were therefore commonly considered a single unit.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] However, an effort was made with the Java 7 specification to more clearly treat the Java language and the Java virtual machine as separate entities, so that they are no longer considered a single unit.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Third parties have produced many compilers or interpreters that target the JVM.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Some of these are for existing languages, while others are for extensions to the Java language.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Like Java, .NET languages compile to byte code and are executed by the Common Language Runtime (CLR), which is similar in purpose to the JVM.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Like the JVM, the CLR provides memory management through automatic garbage collection, and allows .NET byte code to run on multiple operating systems.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] .NET included a Java-like language first named J++, then called Visual J# that was incompatible with the Java specification.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] It was discontinued 2007, and support for it ended in 2015.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The JVM specification gives a lot of leeway to implementors regarding the implementation details.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Since Java 1.3, JRE from Oracle contains a JVM called HotSpot.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] It has been designed to be a high-performance JVM.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] To speed-up code execution, HotSpot relies on just-in-time compilation.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] To speed-up object allocation and garbage collection, HotSpot uses generational heap.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The *Java virtual machine heap* is the area of memory used by the JVM for dynamic memory allocation.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The *permanent generation* (or *permgen*) was used for class definitions and associated metadata prior to Java 8.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Permanent generation was not part of the heap.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The *permanent generation* was removed from Java 8.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Originally there was no permanent generation, and objects and classes were stored together in the same area.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] But as class unloading occurs much more rarely than objects are collected, moving class structures to a specific area allowed significant performance improvements.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Java JRE is installed on a large number of computers.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] End users with an out-of-date version of JRE therefore are vulnerable to many known attacks.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] This led to the widely shared belief that Java is inherently insecure.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Since Java 1.7, Oracle's JRE for Windows includes automatic update functionality.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Before the discontinuation of the Java browser plug-in, any web page might have potentially run a Java applet, which provided an easily accessible attack surface to malicious web sites.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In 2013, Kaspersky Labs reported that the Java plug-in was the method of choice for computer criminals.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java exploits are included in many exploit packs that hackers deploy onto hacked web sites.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java applets were removed in Java 11, released on September 25, 2018.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java began as an internal project at Sun Microsystems in December 1990, providing an alternative to the C++/C programming languages.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Engineer Patrick Naughton had become increasingly frustrated with the state of Sun's C++ and C application programming interfaces (APIs) and tools, as well as with the way the NeWS project was handled by the organization.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Naughton informed Scott McNealy about his plan of leaving Sun and moving to NeXT; McNealy asked him to pretend he was God and send him an e-mail explaining how to fix the company.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Naughton envisioned the creation of a small team that could work autonomously without the bureaucracy that was stalling other Sun projects.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] McNealy forwarded the message to other important people at Sun, and the *Stealth Project* started.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Stealth Project was soon renamed to the *Green Project*, with James Gosling and Mike Sheridan joining Naughton.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Together with other engineers, they began work in a small office on Sand Hill Road in Menlo Park, California.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] They aimed to develop new technology for programming next-generation smart appliances, which Sun expected to offer major new opportunities.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The team originally considered using C++, but rejected it for several reasons.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Because they were developing an embedded system with limited resources, they decided that C++ needed too much memory and that its complexity led to developer errors.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The language's lack of garbage collection meant that programmers had to manually manage system memory, a challenging and error-prone task.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The team also worried about the C++ language's lack of portable facilities for security, distributed programming, and threading.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Finally, they wanted a platform that would port easily to all types of devices.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Bill Joy had envisioned a new language combining Mesa and C.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In a paper called *Further*, he proposed to Sun that its engineers should produce an object-oriented environment based on C++.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Initially, Gosling attempted to modify and extend C++ (a proposed development that he referred to as "C++ ++ --") but soon abandoned that in favor of creating a new language, which he called *Oak*, after the tree that stood just outside his office.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] By the summer of 1992, the team could demonstrate portions of the new platform, including the Green OS, the Oak language, the libraries, and the hardware.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Their first demonstration, on September 3, 1992, focused on building a personal digital assistant (PDA) device named *Star7* that had a graphical interface and a smart agent called "Duke" to assist the user.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In November of that year, the Green Project was spun off to become *Firstperson*, a wholly owned subsidiary of Sun Microsystems, and the team relocated to Palo Alto, California.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Firstperson team had an interest in building highly interactive devices, and when Time Warner issued a request for proposal (RFP) for a set-top box, Firstperson changed their target and responded with a proposal for a set-top box platform.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] However, the cable industry felt that their platform gave too much control to the user, so Firstperson lost their bid to SGI.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] An additional deal with The 3DO Company for a set-top box also failed to materialize.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Unable to generate interest within the television industry, the company was rolled back into Sun.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In June and July 1994 – after three days of brainstorming with John Gage (the Director of Science for Sun), Gosling, Joy, Naughton, Wayne Rosing, and Eric Schmidt – the team re-targeted the platform for the World Wide Web.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] They felt that with the advent of graphical web browsers like Mosaic the Internet could evolve into the same highly interactive medium that they had envisioned for cable TV.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] As a prototype, Naughton wrote a small browser, WebRunner (named after the movie *Blade Runner*), renamed HotJava in 1995.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Sun renamed the Oak language to *Java* after a trademark search revealed that Oak Technology used the name *Oak*.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Sun priced Java licenses below cost to gain market share.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Although Java 1.0a became available for download in 1994, the first public release of Java, Java 1.0a2 with the HotJava browser, came on May 23, 1995, announced by Gage at the SunWorld conference.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Accompanying Gage's announcement, Marc Andreessen, Executive Vice President of Netscape Communications Corporation, unexpectedly announced that Netscape browsers would include Java support.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] On January 9, 1996, Sun Microsystems formed the JavaSoft group to develop the technology.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] On November 13, 2006, Sun Microsystems made the bulk of its implementation of Java available under the GNU General Public License (GPL).
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Java language has undergone several changes since the release of JDK (Java Development Kit) 1.0 on January 23, 1996, as well as numerous additions of classes and packages to the standard library.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Since J2SE 1.4 the Java Community Process (JCP) has governed the evolution of the Java Language.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The JCP uses *Java Specification Requests* (JSRs) to propose and specify additions and changes to the Java platform.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The *Java Language Specification* (JLS) specifies the language; changes to the JLS are managed under JSR 901.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Major additions included an extensive retooling of the Abstract Window Toolkit (AWT) event model, inner classes added to the language, JavaBeans, and Java Database Connectivity (JDBC).
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In June 2016, after the last public update of Java 7, "remotely exploitable" security bugs in Java 6, 7, and 8 were announced.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In addition to language changes, significant changes have been made to the Java class library over the years, which has grown from a few hundred classes in JDK 1.0 to over three thousand in J2SE 5.0.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Entire new APIs, such as Swing and Java 2D, have evolved, and many of the original JDK 1.0 classes and methods have been deprecated (thereof some "terminally deprecated"), e.g. related to finalization.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] At least one very rarely-used API (for threading) has been removed from Java 22.
