[src:javafx/java-software-platform] According to Oracle in 2010, the Java Runtime Environment was found on over 850 million PCs.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Microsoft has not bundled a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) with its operating systems since Sun Microsystems sued Microsoft for adding Windows-specific classes to the bundled Java runtime environment, and for making the new classes available through Visual J++.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Apple no longer includes a Java runtime with OS X as of version 10.7, but the system prompts the user to download and install it the first time an application requiring the JRE is launched.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Many Linux distributions include the OpenJDK runtime as the default virtual machine, negating the need to download the proprietary Oracle JRE.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Some Java applications are in fairly widespread desktop use, including the NetBeans, Eclipse and JetBrains integrated development environments, and file sharing clients such as LimeWire and Vuze.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java is also used in the MATLAB mathematics programming environment, both for rendering the user interface and as part of the core system.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java provides cross platform user interface for some high end collaborative applications such as Lotus Notes.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Oracle plans to first deprecate the separately installable Java browser plugin from the Java Runtime Environment in JDK 9 then remove it completely from a future release, forcing web developers to use an alternative technology.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] When Sun announced that Java SE and Java ME would be released under a free software license (the GNU General Public License), they released the Duke graphics under the free BSD license at the same time.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] A new Duke personality is created every year.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] For example, in July 2011 "Future Tech Duke" included a bigger nose, a jetpack, and blue wings.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The source code for Sun's implementations of Java (i.e. the de facto reference implementation) has been available for some time, but until recently, the license terms severely restricted what could be done with it without signing (and generally paying for) a contract with Sun.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] As such these terms did not satisfy the requirements of either the Open Source Initiative or the Free Software Foundation to be considered open source or free software, and Sun Java was therefore a proprietary platform.
