[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Schwartz said that the company was set to announce the release of the core Java Platform as free and open source software within 30 to 60 days.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] According to Richard Stallman, this would mean an end to the "Java trap".
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Mark Shuttleworth called the initial press announcement, "A real milestone for the free software community".
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Sun released the source code of the Class library under GPL on May 8, 2007, except some limited parts that were licensed by Sun from third parties who did not want their code to be released under a free software and open-source license.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Some of the encumbered parts turned out to be fairly key parts of the platform such as font rendering and 2D rasterizing, but these were released as open-source later by Sun (see OpenJDK Class library).
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Sun's goal was to replace the parts that remain proprietary and closed-source with alternative implementations and make the class library completely free and open source.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In the meantime, a third-party project called IcedTea created a completely free and highly usable JDK by replacing encumbered code with either stubs or code from GNU Classpath.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] However OpenJDK has since become buildable without the encumbered parts (from OpenJDK 6 b10) and has become the default runtime environment for most Linux distributions.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In June 2008, it was announced that IcedTea6 (as the packaged version of OpenJDK on Fedora 9) has passed the Technology Compatibility Kit tests and can claim to be a fully compatible Java 6 implementation.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Because OpenJDK is under the GPL, it is possible to redistribute a custom version of the JRE directly with software applications, rather than requiring the enduser (or their sysadmin) to download and install the correct version of the proprietary Oracle JRE onto each of their systems themselves.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In most cases, Java support is unnecessary in Web browsers, and security experts recommend that it not be run in a browser unless absolutely necessary.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] It was suggested that, if Java is required by a few Web sites, users should have a separate browser installation specifically for those sites.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] When generics were added to Java 5.0, there was already a large framework of classes (many of which were already deprecated), so generics were chosen to be implemented using erasure to allow for *migration compatibility* and re-use of these existing classes.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] This limited the features that could be provided by this addition as compared to some other languages.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The addition of type wildcards made Java unsound.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java lacks native unsigned integer types.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Unsigned data are often generated from programs written in C and the lack of these types prevents direct data interchange between C and Java.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Unsigned large numbers are also used in many numeric processing fields, including cryptography, which can make Java less convenient to use for these tasks.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Although it is possible to partially circumvent this problem with conversion code and using larger data types, it makes using Java cumbersome for handling the unsigned data.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] While a 32-bit signed integer may be used to hold a 16-bit unsigned value with relative ease, a 32-bit unsigned value would require a 64-bit signed integer.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Additionally, a 64-bit unsigned value cannot be stored using any integer type in Java because no type larger than 64 bits exists in the Java language.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] If abstracted using functions, function calls become necessary for many operations which are native to some other languages.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Alternatively, it is possible to use Java's signed integers to emulate unsigned integers of the same size, but this requires detailed knowledge of complex bitwise operations.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java's floating-point arithmetic is largely based on IEEE 754 (*Standard for Binary Floating-Point Arithmetic*), but certain features are not supported even when using the `strictfp` modifier, such as Exception Flags and Directed Roundings – capabilities mandated by IEEE Standard 754.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Additionally, the extended-precision floating-point types permitted in 754 and present in many processors are not permitted in Java.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In the early days of Java (before the HotSpot VM was implemented in Java 1.3 in 2000) there were some criticisms of performance.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Benchmarks typically reported Java as being about 50% slower than C (a language which compiles to native code).
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java's performance has improved substantially since the early versions.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Performance of JIT compilers relative to native compilers has in some optimized tests been shown to be quite similar.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java bytecode can either be interpreted at run time by a virtual machine, or it can be compiled at load time or runtime into native code which runs directly on the computer's hardware.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Interpretation is slower than native execution, and compilation at load time or runtime has an initial performance penalty for the compilation.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Modern performant JVM implementations all use the compilation approach, so after the initial startup time the performance is equivalent to native code.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Java platform provides a security architecture which is designed to allow the user to run untrusted bytecode in a "sandboxed" manner to protect against malicious or poorly written software.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] This "sandboxing" feature is intended to protect the user by restricting access to certain platform features and APIs which could be exploited by malware, such as accessing the local filesystem, running arbitrary commands, or accessing communication networks.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In recent years, researchers have discovered numerous security flaws in some widely used Java implementations, including Oracle's, which allow untrusted code to bypass the sandboxing mechanism, exposing users to malicious attacks.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] These flaws affect only Java applications which execute arbitrary untrusted bytecode, such as web browser plug-ins that run Java applets downloaded from public websites.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Applications where the user trusts, and has full control over, all code that is being executed are unaffected.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] On August 31, 2012, Java 6 and 7 (both supported back then) on Microsoft Windows, OS X, and Linux were found to have a serious security flaw that allowed a remote exploit to take place by simply loading a malicious web page.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java 5 was later found to be flawed as well.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] On January 10, 2013, three computer specialists spoke out against Java, telling Reuters that it was not secure and that people should disable Java.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Jaime Blasco, Labs Manager with AlienVault Labs, stated that "Java is a mess.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] You have to disable it." This vulnerability affects Java 7 and it is unclear if it affects Java 6, so it is suggested that consumers disable it.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Security alerts from Oracle announce schedules of critical security-related patches to Java.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] On January 14, 2013, security experts said that the update still failed to protect PCs from attack.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] This exploit hole prompted a response from the United States Department of Homeland Security encouraging users to disable or uninstall Java.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Apple blacklisted Java in limited order for all computers running its OS X operating system through a virus protection program.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] In 2014 and responding to then-recent Java security and vulnerability issues, security blogger Brian Krebs has called for users to remove at least the Java browser plugin and also the entire software.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] If you are a typical home user, you can probably do without it.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] The Oracle-distributed Java runtime environment has a history of bundling sponsored software to be installed by default during installation and during the updates which roll out every month or so.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] This includes the "Ask.com toolbar" that will redirect browser searches to ads and "McAfee Security Scan Plus".
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] These offers can be blocked through a setting in the Java Control Panel, although this is not obvious.
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] This setting is located under the "Advanced" tab in the Java Control Panel, under the "Miscellaneous" heading, where the option is labelled as an option to suppress "sponsor offers".
[src:javafx/java-software-platform] Java has yet to release an automatic updater that does not require user intervention and administrative rights unlike Google Chrome and Flash player.
